Introduction 

This project is part of my role as a Student Digital Ambassador at VIT Bhopal University. 
The primary objective is to help peers navigate the digital world safely and professionally 
by creating a comprehensive Digital Literacy Portfolio. This report documents five specific 
tasks ranging from visual design and professional networking to coding, communication etiquette,
and cybercrime awareness. Each module is designed to build foundational digital skills necessary 
for a successful academic and professional career.

Task 1 Write-up: Digital Literacy Awareness Infographic 

For this task, I created a one-page visual resource using Canva to help my batchmates understand 
essential digital concepts. My design focuses on safe internet practices, useful digital tools for
students, and professional online presence. The infographic uses clear icons and bullet points to 
make the information easily digestible. One thing I found interesting was how much information can
be conveyed through simple visual hierarchy without using dense text. This tool will be useful for
any future academic presentations I need to design.

Task 2 Write-up: Build Your Student Digital Portfolio 

I set up my professional foundation by creating and updating profiles on GitHub, LinkedIn, and Kaggle.
On GitHub, I created a profile README that introduces my branch, year, and learning goals. On LinkedIn, 
I added my current education at VIT Bhopal to ensure I am visible to the academic community. These
platforms are essential for networking and showcasing my technical work. Over the next four years, 
I plan to use GitHub for version control of my coding projects and LinkedIn to connect with industry
experts for internship opportunities.

Task 3 Write-up: Explore Coding & Collaboration Platforms 

In the coding section of this task, I used CodeChef to solve a beginner-level programming challenge.
This helped me practice basic logic and familiarized me with competitive programming environments. 
For the collaboration part, I used Google Forms to build a 'Digital Literacy Awareness Quiz' with five 
questions, including multiple-choice and short-answer formats. I also linked the form to a Google Sheet
to manage responses. These tools are vital for academic group projects as they allow for efficient data
collection and real-time collaboration.

Task 4 Write-up: Draft a Professional Email & Etiquette Guide

This task involved practicing professional communication by drafting two emails: one to a professor for
an assignment extension and another to an internship coordinator. I focused on maintaining a formal tone, 
clear subject lines, and proper sign-offs. I also developed a checklist of 5 Do’s and 5 Don’ts for social
media use. A key learning was how poor digital communication—such as an unprofessional subject line—can lead
to important emails being ignored or misunderstood in a professional setting.

Task 5 Write-up: Cybercrime Awareness Case Study & Prevention 
While researching the UPI/Online Payment Fraud case study, I was most surprised by how scammers use psychological
tricks like "cashback" to make users enter their PINs. It is alarming how a single click can lead to total 
financial loss. As a result of this research, one habit I will personally change is to never click on suspicious 
links in SMS and to always verify the recipient's name before any transaction. I have also noted the 1930 helpline
as a critical resource for reporting such crimes.

Conclusion 

Completing this project has significantly improved mydigital literacy and professional preparedness. 
I have learned to manage my online identity, collaborate using cloud tools, and communicate with academic 
and professional etiquette. Most importantly, I have gained the knowledge to identify and prevent common 
cybercrimes. These skills will serve as a strong foundation for my fouryears at VIT Bhopal and my future 
career in technology.

